Spandau was a prison in Berlin where Nazis were hanged. When people are being hanged and they're just about to die, they do a jerky movement, and that got nicknamed the Spandau Ballet. As a CEO, I have received a lot of feedback about onboarding, and I’m proud to say that I’ve heard from many people that Clockwork's the best process they’ve been through in starting in a new company. A lot of that is in large part due to the leadership team here who is always thinking about ways to improve that process because it can be so overwhelming.  So, how do we do it? Here are 3 things I think are important to our onboarding process: 1️⃣🗓 We schedule everybody out for the first two weeks. So they have one-on-ones with the leadership team, they’re assigned a buddy who they’ll then work with who will show them the ropes. They have a series of conversations, protocols and policies to read, and they have a person that’s advocating for them and helping them navigate their way in this unfamiliar place. 2️⃣🧠 We are in the habit of hiring really smart people. When that happens, you have a lot of people who are used to being the smartest person in the room. I think just realizing that you’re not the only one anymore and settling into the rhythm of a group of people, a team of people, that operate from that place, is a challenge. voice_to_text: Japanese categorizes nouns in 500+ different ways. Similar to how Spanish divides nouns into feminine and masculine, Japanese splits items into their own categories. Unlike Spanish, however, Japanese does not consider these categories as grammatical gender. Instead, they are a part of a system called counterwords, which are a specific way of counting items depending on their category. For instance, if you know the numbers in Japanese, then you know that they are each ni sashi go rokushi t hatsuki do. So what if you were at a Japanese restaurant and wanted to order two of the same thing? You might think that you can just say ni could I say? But this is incorrect. If you want to count actual things, you need to use a whole different set of numbers, which are as follows itotsu, itatsu, mitsu, iotsu, itsutsu, mutsu, nanatsu, yatsu, coconutsu, and Toh. So in a restaurant you'd actually say something like Huttatsu Kurasai. Okay, so what if you wanted to count the amount of bottles on a counter? Well, you could just use the same thing as before, Huttatsu, Huttatsu, etc. it would sound much more natural if you used a different counterword, which is specifically or long thin objects, which is Hong. So you count the bottles by saying Eek horn, ni horn, sam Bon, Yong horn, go horn, drop horn, Nana horn, hatsy horn, q horn, jup horn. There are way more kind of words than just the two that I just Gave. For example, there's a counterword for counting animals there. On the smaller side, Kiki. Then there's a counterword for big animals like elephants. Pole. There's also one for machines, people, cans, volumes of books, and so many more. He has highlighted the multitude of specific days and months dedicated to this lifestyle, questioning the necessity of such extensive observances and labeling the lifestyle as an abomination according to the Bible. Bishop Wooden's passionate stance against what he perceives as an aggressive promotion of LGBTQ+ views onto society underscores his unwavering commitment to his faith and beliefs. He voices concern over the forceful imposition of these celebrations, emphasizing that as believers, they will not passively accept it. In his powerful message, Bishop Wooden asserts, "Do you see how wicked this is? They are trying to ram this stuff down our throats, and as believers, we are not going to allow them to do that." His resolute stand reflects a deep-rooted conviction in upholding the teachings of the Bible and resisting what he views as a cultural shift contrary to his religious beliefs. In a world where diverse perspectives coexist, Bishop Wooden's outspoken views serve as a reminder of the importance of standing firm in one's faith and convictions. While sparking debate and controversy, his message underscores the significance of staying true to one's beliefs in the face of societal pressures and trends. As we navigate discussions around LGBTQ+ rights and celebrations, Bishop Wooden's words provoke reflection on the balance between tolerance, acceptance, and the preservation of individual beliefs. His unwavering stance calls for a respectful dialogue that acknowledges differing viewpoints while upholding the values that hold significance for each individual. In a society where diversity and inclusivity are celebrated, Bishop Wooden's voice serves as a reminder of the importance of respecting differing perspectives while staying true to one's principles.
